* issue: does not end cleanly after installing MADlib so you need to manually exit via ctl-z,  however the MADlib install actually completed OK.

* issue: some failures may happen on MADlib install checks

  12:55 PM
The get_estimates parameter controls computation for two statistics:
If get_estimates is TRUE then the distinct value computation is estimated. Further, the most frequent values computation is computed using a "quick and dirty" method that does parallel aggregation in Greenplum Database at the expense of missing some of the most frequent values.
If get_estimates is FALSE then the distinct values are computed in a slow but exact method. The most frequent values are computed using a faithful implementation that preserves the approximation guarantees of the Cormode/Muthukrishnan method (more information in MFV (Most Frequent Values)).

--migrate GPHOME_1 GPHOME_2


Migrates packages from a separate $GPHOME. Carries over packages from one version of Greenplum Database to another.


For example: gppkg --migrate /usr/local/greenplum-db-4.2.0.1 /usr/local/greenplum-db-4.2.1.0


This option is automatically invoked by the installer during minor upgrades. This option is given here for cases when the user wants to migrate packages manually.


Migration can only proceed if gppkg is executed from the installation directory to which packages are being migrated. That is, GPHOME_2 must match the $GPHOME from which the currently executing gppkg is being run.

@manningj: Could you please describe how you perform the DB upgrade? We’re currently working to add this feature and would like to test your use case. Thanks.






  3:21 AM
When upgrading from 4.3.9.1 to 4.3.10.0, it is just a binary change. Shutdown the DB. Run the GPDB .bin file extracted from the downloaded .zip file to install the binaries on the master host. Source the new environment source /usr/local/greenplum-db-4.3.10.0/greenplum_path.sh. Then run gpseginstall to install the SW on all the segment hosts. Change the /usr/local/greenplum-db softlink on each host and the start the DB.


3:25
As a hack/test in the lab, I updated the table madlib.migrationhistory to change the “version” to “1.9” and then ran an upgrade to 1.9,1 and all the paths got updated successfully and all user views using the schema were kept.

Chore - ci: madlib gpdb IC planner jobs do not turn optimizer offDescription
1. All our gpdb planner jobs are running with orca set to on instead of off. This is because of the following line in disable_orca.bash
psql postgres -c "ALTER DATABASE postgres SET OPTIMIZER = OFF;"
This sql query turns orca off for the postgres database and not the database that install-check and dev-check run on. 1. Because of this, our gpdb tests were never running with planner. Hence we never caught another bug in our test code in the function update_dist_keys in test/madlib_keras_fit_multiple.sql_in. The update statement fails on gpdb5 planner with the following error
